      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Candidates' Plans, Tested on the Web</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Mark J Eisner letter on Paul Krugman's Sept 13 column on Gov George W Bush's economic plan; urges nonpartisan group set up Web site that lets voters test viability of each candidate's economic plan; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Paul Krugman (column, Sept. 13) says George W. Bush's economic plan does not add up. Governor Bush says it will. The voter is left bewildered, unnecessarily so. With so many Americans using personal computer software or the Web to analyze their personal financial futures under various economic assumptions, cannot some nonpartisan organization set up a Web site that lets voters test the viability of each candidate's economic plan?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Paul Krugman (column, Sept. 13) says George W. Bush's economic plan does not add up. Governor Bush says it will. The voter is left bewildered, unnecessarily so. With so many Americans using personal computer software or the Web to analyze their personal financial futures under various economic assumptions, cannot some nonpartisan organization set up a Web site that lets voters test the viability of each candidate's economic plan?</p>
        <p>The site could incorporate Congressional Budget Office projections and help voters make meaningful assumptions about rates of inflation, economic growth and other details. It could then calculate the projected consequences for Social Security, Medicare, new programs and taxes in coming years and show them to the voter. The Internet is democratizing the flow of information. Why not use it to further democratize the political process as well?</p>
        <p>MARK J. EISNER  Ithaca, N.Y., Sept. 13, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a lecturer in information technology at Cornell University.</p>
      </block>
